ing=1><tr><td valign=top bgcolor=#666eb0 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=#666eb0 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 376<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/6/03 8:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Camille's eyes, even before they pierced the gloom, knew where she was.<br>
<br>
The lair of Terris Thule.<br>
<br>
Terris still lay on the ground where Camille had seen her last, dress shredded around her, soaked in caked blood. Most of the puddles of blood had reduced themselves to dry dark stains on the floor. Terris' wounds were all gone, without a scar, but she did not move.<br>
<br>
~~dismount~~ came that disembodied voice, but now with some direction. It was coming from Terris herself.<br>
<br>
Camille, for the first time since the insane journey had begun, loosened her leg muscles and released her grip on Brimstone's mane. She half slid, half fell off the horse, exhausted, every sinew screaming. She landed uneasily on her feet, and then just slid abruptly to the ground, panting. She feared she would never walk again.<br>
<br>
Slowly, painstakingly, Terris rolled over, without a sound of rustled cloth, to lay on her side and yet look upon Camille. The goddess' breast heaved as her nostrils flared out and in, taking in air. Her huge dark eyes scrutinized the sprawled out paladin, dressed only in her sleeping gown, still clutching her husband's sword.<br>
<br>
For a long time they just contemplated each other silently.<br>
<br>
~~you are a strong woman, to have survived that~~<br>
<br>
&quot;So are you,&quot; Camille remarked, looking at the dark stains on the ground.<br>
<br>
~~i am a goddess, i will never truly die, until the day mortals finally succeed in their little dream of conquest, and kill us all in the plane of time ~ then they can see how they like a world with no gods ~ akethadar and his dogs did not kill me, just my avatar, and slowly, over time i will be whole again ~ and then i suppose they will be back, as mortals always are ~ although i imagine akethadar will not be leading the next set, no no~~ and the sound of a chuckle that chilled Camille.<br>
<br>
&quot;Did you drive Akethadar mad?&quot; Camille asked bluntly.<br>
<br>
~~me?~~ Terris asked, actually surprised, ~~i wouldn't touch that man's mind even if the nameless commanded me to ~ no, camille wyldechylde, the only mind i have touched in quite a while has been yours~~<br>
<br>
&quot;The dreams. You sent them to me.&quot;<br>
<br>
~~yes ~ garbled at first as i was weak, very weak ~ later stronger ones, and finally, the will to have the horse bring you here~~<br>
<br>
&quot;If you didn't read Akethadar's mind, why the statue of River?&quot; Camille asked, so many questions bouncing around in her mind. &quot;How would you know?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~ah, the statue~~ Terris said, ~~it was here for the last year ~ where did you think your husband's soul went, to innoruuk? ~ in the end he chose me to worship~~<br>
<br>
&quot;I see.&quot; Camille said shortly, hurt in some undescribable way, unable to stop a pang of jealousy from striking her heart. Terris picked up on it.<br>
<br>
~~ah, you mistake the term worship, mithaniel's handmaiden ~ when faced with which plane his soul would reside in, he chose me, for whatever effect our business with end game had had on him ~ but, from the state of his dreams when he was here, he dreamed of you ~ only you~~<br>
<br>
Camille didn't know whether Terris had said that to appease her or was speaking the truth, but the words acted as a salve for her pained heart. But still her question was unanswered.<br>
<br>
&quot;So you erected a statue of him here?&quot; Camille asked, confused.<br>
<br>
~~no~~ Terris replied, ~~that was no statue of any rock known to man ~ that was a soulcasing, my own creation ~ you saw my gargoyles, they are of the same stone~~<br>
<br>
&quot;Soulcasing.&quot; Camille said blankly.<br>
<br>
~~yes, my other four worshipers, yes, only four, were all demons, and thus their likenesses as grotesque ~ the soulcasing can hold the living soul that exists after the body dies~~<br>
<br>
&quot;So when River died,&quot; Camille said, hope lighting her face as stared at Terris. &quot;He did not die?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~yes, and no~~ Terris said. ~~the soul if preserved will never truly die, so while his time among mortals was done, he lived on dreaming in the soulcasing i provided for him ~ in times of dire stress, i wake the dreamers to protect me, but river ~~~ would not ~ you saw that~<br>
<br>
&quot;I saw.&quot; Camille replied, recalling the dream.<br>
<br>
~~he suspected that i would eventually survive the attack, while promethian would not ~ even against his sworn enemy he would not attack with the strength the soulcasing would have lended him~~<br>
<br>
&quot;River didn't hate Akethadar.&quot; Camille said.<br>
<br>
~~but akethadar hated him ~ oh how he hated him ~ and grieg saw that, saw the statue in akethadar's mind, even as he died, and jumped on it~~<br>
<br>
&quot;Grieg.&quot; Camille said, seizing upon the name to change subjects to more of her questions. &quot;Where does he fit into this?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~grieg veneficus was a brilliant geomancer, the top of his class ~ long ago his studies with the magic inherant in stone and earth allowed for travel to luclin, where he brought the combine ~ when he failed to discover a route back in timely fashion, however, he was spurned, and forced into his castle to discover a route back ~ but luclin the deity was enjoying the new additions to her little world, and drove grieg mad in his home, and set up clever mind-altering guardians to guard both him ever leaving his castle and anyone entering ~ the insanity also had the unusual side effect of keeping him alive long after he should have died, as his body rotted and changed into a blobbish purple mass ~ grieg festered like an open wound in his home while others finally found a way to open a two way portal to the moon, and was forgotten ~ but he never forgot the outside world, or the wrongs they had suffered upon him~~<br>
<br>
Slowly Terris propped herself up into a sitting position, and continued.<br>
<br>
~~over the years of his imprisonment, grieg had still worked on his experiments, but now for his own dark purpose ~ one of these was the creation of a blue gem that he called the geomancer's stone ~ the gem was part prison, part battery~~<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't understand.&quot; Camille cut in.<br>
<br>
~~patience, mithaniel's handmaiden~~ Terris shhed her, then went on as Camille fell silent, more questions dying on her lips. ~~the geomancer's stone could act as a housing for a soul without a soulcasing, to preserve the soul, very similiar to what the statue of riverdane could do ~ and once a soul was inside it, could be used as a power source for mechanical devices, drawing on the lifeforce of the soul within, consuming it as it magnified that lifeforce to energy many many times the size of the actual soul ~ eventually, the soul would be snuffed out, but the power output would be astronomical~~<br>
<br>
&quot;My dreams.&quot; Camille said, face pale, &quot;River....is in that gem.&quot;<br>
<br>
~~yes~~ Terris confirmed. ~~when akethadar killed grieg, grieg tapped his mind and saw the statue, and knowing more about stone than any other living man, knew the soulcasing for what it was ~ he planted the seed of insanity into akethadar's brain, like a parasite, and then escaped with his own soul into the geomancer's stone, and waited ~ waited for akethadar's mind to be eaten away, and to answer the hypnotic order greig had placed in him ~ to deliver the statue to the moon ~ grieg's servants, local natives whom grieg's magic had bound and twisted, recovered the statue and brought it to the geomancer's stone, where grieg, powered with insanity and taking riverdane quite by surprise, forced riverdane's soul out of the soulcasing and took his place ~ river, having no other place to go, slipped into the geomancer's stone~<br>
<br>
&quot;River...&quot; Camille said helplessly.<br>
<br>
~~is trapped~~ Terris continued. ~~now grieg has a form that can move and is nearly indestructable in one on one combat ~ and riverdane is trapped in the geomancer's stone, unable to leave, with nowhere to go ~ and freedom is not the only thing grieg wanted ~ he is currently working on another experiment, and i suspect he intends to use river's soul to power it ~ grieg's mind is too twisted to read, and he does not dream, not for even a second ~ the insanity luclin placed on him ate any capacity he had for dreams ~ so i do not know what the madman is planning to do, only that river's soul is in great peril, and knowing grieg's insanity, so are a great many more~~<br>
<br>
&quot;River was trying to tell me something. YOU were trying to tell me something!&quot; Camille exclaimed, panic in her tone. &quot;What does 'Avenge' have to do with this? Avenge River? You?&quot;<br>
<br>
Terris stared blankly at her. ~~avenge?~~<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes!&quot; Camille said with frustration. &quot;In the dream, River said 'Avenge', 'Venge'; you, YOU said 'Venge'!&quot; But Terris just continued to stare at her with no comprehension in her eyes. Then suddenly, Terris' eyes narrowed a moment.<br>
<br>
~~ahh, no, not avenge~~ Terris said. ~~it never fails to amaze me how you mortals hear things and don't hear, twisting things to suit what you think they mean ~ the word i wanted you to hear was vven~~<br>
<br>
&quot;Ven?&quot; Camille asked, confused.<br>
<br>
~~two v's~~ Terris sighed.<br>
<br>
Camille's mouth dropped open, as she began to understand. &quot;Vven? The enchanter that helped River during End Game?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~yes~~<br>
<br>
&quot;How does Vven figure into this at all?&quot; Camille asked, confused again.<br>
<br>
~~when your husband and his companions were here, i opened up his mind, to read his past and his intentions ~ his friends suspected i was also picking through their minds ~ and they were right ~ i remember a fragment from vven of a meeting at some point in his life with grieg, a flash in time, but i remember it ~ enough so for me to believe that vven psyphon may have more information on grieg's intent, even though the teir'dal may not realize it himself ~ seek him, and find answers~~<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you, Terris.&quot; Camille said softly, reaching out to place her palm over the goddess' massive hand. Terris allowed it, an odd look in her eyes at the woman's touch of sisterhood. &quot;Why? Why did you tell me all this?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~you love him~~ Terris said after a pause. ~~a year ago, riverdane wyldechylde helped return my love to me~i am repaying that favor~~ A pause and then, ~~and he was the only mortal other than demons to choose me~~<br>
<br>
Camille nodded, understanding. Then her eyes suddenly brimmed with tears. &quot;And the dreams, River talking to me, holding me....was that really him or...?&quot;<br>
<br>
~~that was me~~ Terris said sadly. ~~trace memories from him lending me script for the dream ~ i am sorry i made you think he was speaking to you~~<br>
<br>
Camille wiped her eyes as that sunk in. Knights don't cry. &quot;Thank you all the same. Even in a nightmare, it helped keep him alive for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
~~mount the horse, mithaniel's handmaiden~~ Terris said gently. ~~i promise you safe passage back to your home~~ She laboriously drew herself from her feet, and lifted Camille up like a doll to place her on the back of Brimstone, still clutching River's sword. Then Terris passed her hand in front of Camille's eyes.<br>
<br>
~~sleep~~ Terris intoned, and Camille collapsed weakly against Brimstone's neck, deep in slumber. Terris sent her magic out into the woman to keep her from sliding off.<br>
<br>
~~sleep, camille wyldechylde, and for your lost nights in my nightmares, dream of what you wish~~ Terris commanded the paladin in her nightdress, sword hanging from one limp hand. <br>
<br>
~~bring her safely back to the stables, brimstone~~ Terris said quietly.<br>
<br>
--YES, MISTRESS.-- the horse whinnied, unable to disobey. Terris slumped weakly to her knees, the whole conversation having drained more out of her than she would have preferred.<br>
<br>
~~and fetch rallos to me~~ <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 377<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/7/03 3:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Camille Swordswinger, she thought to herself.<br>
<br>
Her nose wrinkled at the thought, as she lifted an armored foot out of the sand and plodded through the featureless desert of North Ro.<br>
<br>
Camille Stunqueen.<br>
<br>
&quot;Eww.&quot; she said out loud. &quot;Appropriate but eww....&quot;<br>
<br>
A passing sand scarab clicked on by, and she regarded it for a moment.<br>
<br>
&quot;I need a surname!&quot; she mock plead.<br>
<br>
-clickclickclick- the sand scarab clicked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Clickclick.&quot; Camille tried. &quot;Sorry, Mr. Scarab, catchy but no.&quot;<br>
<br>
She was nineteen years old, and at the point of her training with the Knights of Truth in North Freeport was reaching the level where she could choose a last name. Easier said than done.<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't want to be Camille Spelldancer all my life.&quot; she sighed, marching across the dunes. &quot;I'm not even a caster!&quot;<br>
<br>
True. Her parents were both pure casters, and were secretly, she suspected, horrified that she had decided to become a melee. But for most of her childhood, she had watched the Knights of Truth jousting and training with the look of hero worship in her eyes. And then into her tumulent teens, and the handsome blonde knights with their razor short hair and piercing blue eyes and shining armor. She had giggled like a typical teenage girl with her friends, watching the knights battle in training sessions. But then, when she hit sixteen, she stopped giggling, and started watching closer. Her other friends disappeared, as she began staying at home more, practicing with a stick feints and parries, to the growing distress of her parents. And a year later, on her seventeenth birthday, she marched into the recruiting office of the Knights of Truth and signed on. And her life changed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Bladeweilder.&quot; she tried lamely.<br>
<br>
Now she was one of those 'knights in shining armor'. And she learned something, being part of them, training with them. They were just boys, just like the others her age. Immature, some of them mean, some of them stupid. And they all treated her, during the training sessions, like a...well...like a girl.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Dlere.&quot; she tried. Double ewww. Wouldn't he just LOVE that.<br>
<br>
She quickly tossed away the thought of taking on the surname of one of Freeport's most talented knights, Lucan Dlere. He was excellent in training, but he was so....full of himself. He knew he was good, and didn't let any of the other knights-in-training forget it. And when she and he sparred, he let her win, every time, even though she begged him to make it a fair fight. But he just laughed at her, and would fall onto his rump and plead for mercy. He had it in his head to make her his wife when they were older, that she knew. But ever since he tried to touch her where he shouldn't a year ago at the May Festival, she had avoided him like the plague.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Weaponmis....&quot; she began, and then blinked.<br>
<br>
Sand straight ahead.<br>
<br>
Sand to the left.<br>
<br>
Sand to the right.<br>
<br>
Sand behind, and the sun having sunk down to the point where she could not tell where it had been.<br>
<br>
It was growing dark, and there she was, lost somewhere in the middle of North Ro.<br>
<br>
'Oh no...&quot; she whispered, distraught.<br>
<br>
She was lost again.<br>
<br>
Camille had never had a sense for direction, but with the sun to guide her, when the Knights of Truth had impressed upon her a mission to head to the first dervish outpost in North Ro and ascertain if a dark elf was indeed in charge of operations, she had readily set out. And now she was lost, daydreaming the day away and screwing up the first important task the Knights had asked her to perform. She sat down abruptly in the sand, looking helplessly around her, when hot salty tears suddenly found their way to her eyes. Frustration fueled her as she wept.<br>
<br>
&quot;What now, knights don't cry.&quot; came a voice from the side, startling her to her feet and surprising her tears to a halt.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wasn't crying!&quot; she lied hastily, examining the young man who stood atop a dune looking down at her.<br>
<br>
He looked like no knight she had ever seen.<br>
<br>
Long black hair, as long as hers, fell across his forehead and down past his shoulder in the back. A straight handsome nose, with the shadow of hair underneath it, unshaven. Lips in an amicable smile, and eyes, eyes so black they seemed to look right through her. Long lashes, almost....pretty, she would wager, made those eyes something to behold. But his armor! No bracers or gauntlets, patchwork leather arms, a chain tunic with some of the links broken, leather boots, tarnished plate leggings, and a dented sheild. The only thing quality in his attire was the Knights of Truth regulation long sword, which was sheathed at his side. She recognized the insignia on the hilt.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah,&quot; he said, eyes taking her in. &quot;Forgive me, miss. Must have been sand blown in your eyes.&quot; The fact that there was no wind did not escape Camille, but she took his opportunity for an out.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot; she said, removing a steel gauntlet and wiping her eyes free of tears. &quot;Who are you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You can call me River.&quot; he said. &quot;And you are...?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille.&quot; she replied, curiosity in her rising. &quot;You carry a longsword from the Knights of Truth, yet I have never seen you in the guildhouse....River.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, this.&quot; he said, glancing down at the weaponry. &quot;A gift from my father for my twentieth birthday. Beats the old rusty short sword I used to use.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Your father bought it from the Knights for you?&quot; Camille asked with a frown. That was unheard of.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; River said with a laugh. &quot;It was his, before he upgraded. My father is Dane, one of the Knights.&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille surpressed a gasp. She had had a childhood crush on Dane that time had erased. But this long-haired ruffian looked nothing like the blonde, blue eyed Dane who did much of the Knights external affairs work.<br>
<br>
&quot;I did not know Dane had a son.&quot; she remarked casually.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not many do, my father is a private man.&quot; River said. &quot;My mother died in childbirth bringing me into the world, and he has kept to himself since.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm sorry,&quot; Camille said truthfully, but the young man shrugged it off. Then more questions from her.<br>
<br>
&quot;So why have you not applied to the Knights?&quot; she commented. &quot;You could get some real armor and...&quot;<br>
<br>
River laughed suddenly. &quot;I don't think I would make a good Knight.&quot; he said. &quot;I make do with what I can buy or find. You don't like my outfit?&quot; And he turned, posing, self mockery on his face. She had to smile. &quot;Anyway, my father trains me at home, and as he upgrades, I'll get some of his old pieces.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And what is that bit of dirt under your nose?&quot; she asked coyly, pointing at the unshaven hair above his lip.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, that.&quot; River said, face going red. &quot;That, my lady, is a moustache, if it ever grows in. My father says with my long hair I am looking more like my mother each day, so I am growing it to stop torturing him. I think he would prefer I cut my hair, but...no chance there.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It IS an odd look for a man.&quot; she remarked.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm an odd man.&quot; he grinned.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you have a surname?&quot; she asked suddenly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye.&quot; he said. And left it at that.<br>
<br>
&quot;You do?&quot; she asked in surprise. &quot;What is it?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Wyldechylde.&quot; he said, a little embarassed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wyldechylde!&quot; she exclaimed. &quot;How...odd.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm an odd man.&quot; River repeated with a selfconscious smile. &quot;My father used to call me that, remarking on my tendency to throw away the rules of combat when we sparred. I took it half as a joke, but....it seemed fitting.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Very bold of you, to take a surname with no formal training of a guild.&quot; she commented archly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ho ho!&quot; he laughed. &quot;I have all the training I need, Miss Camille...&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille laughed at him shortly. &quot;Oh really?&quot; she said. &quot;Things your father taught you? I cannot imagine they compare to the vigorous training of the Knights of T...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Spar?&quot; River offered, drawing his sword. Camille's heart raced. She loved to spar.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gladly.&quot; she said, drawing her sword. Please don't just let me win, she thought desperately.<br>
<br>
He did not disappoint her.<br>
<br>
Swords locked, their faces close to each other as they pushed toward each other, and the spar began.<br>
<br>
Camille swung each swing, falling into the last two years of training naturally. And she was good, having learned her lessons well. But the young man matched every swing, parrying, feinting, riposting, blocking. They circled around in the sand like two dancers leaping into a delicate, deadly waltz.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're good.&quot; she commented breathlessly, dodging as he lunged forward, escaping the tip of his blade.<br>
<br>
&quot;So are you,&quot; River panted, ducking as she sliced high. &quot;You ARE holding back, yes, I would hate to bleed all over that shiny armor of yours.&quot; And then he swung low, knocking her sword up high.<br>
<br>
Reflexes kicked in, part of her training. Her eyes lit with blue light, and she murmured a short incantation, and a force of air slammed into the young man and stunned him off his feet and onto his rear in the sand. He blinked in surprise, as she swung over her head at him, but he rolled quickly to the side, leaving her sword half buried in the dune.<br>
<br>
&quot;Very nice, very nice!&quot; he remarked, swinging at her side as she brought her sheild between his blade and her armor. It deflected the blow.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm surprised you haven't tried to stun me yet.&quot; she said, circling around him.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can't stun.&quot; River said, circling with her, the two of them like cats in an alley.<br>
<br>
&quot;What?&quot; she said in surprise. Block, parry. &quot;Your father has been remiss in his teachings then.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He tried.&quot; River replied, riposte, dodge. &quot;I can't catch on to it. But there are other ways to stop a caster. Is that sheild of yours for decoration only? You haven't used it except to block.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't need anything but my stuns.&quot; she said confidently, lunge, counter. Blast him, he escaped her blade again.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, realllly.&quot; he singsonged, slowing his movement. &quot;Alright, Miss Stun. Try to stun me again.&quot;<br>
<br>
She stopped moving in circles, and faced him. &quot;Ok.&quot; she agreed, eyes lighting blue.<br>
<br>
SMASH. His sheild came up like a weapon, taking her by surprise, and knocked her flat onto her back, spell dissipating as she momentarily forgot the incarnation. Her head swam.<br>
<br>
&quot;Damned, sorry.&quot; he said honestly, reaching out a hand to help her up. She groggily accepted, as he began to pull her to her feet.<br>
<br>
With a wrench and a roll back, she yanked him off balance and tossed him over her into the sand. Then leaping to her feet, she turned and swung, but his sheild was up and blocking, even from his prone position on the ground.<br>
<br>
&quot;Haha!&quot; he laughed, &quot;Nice try. Now for a bit of MY magic!&quot; and he said something in a gutteral language, and his eyes lit red. Suddenly Camille felt all the strength drain out of her legs, and she pitched forward, drained, unceremoniously landing between the man's legs across his body.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's ok, I just took some of your strength.&quot; he said softly, her faces inches from his as they lay in the sand. &quot;It will come back soon.&quot;<br>
<br>
Their eyes locked. Her cheeks flushed red as her whole body grew warm in his half-embrace.<br>
<br>
Suddenly uncomfortably aware of the position they were in, she jumped to her feet, dusting sand off her armor and not looking down at him, sheathed her sword.<br>
<br>
&quot;Draw?&quot; he offered, climbing to his feet.<br>
<br>
&quot;Draw.&quot; she said shortly, embarrassed at both losing her balance like that and her body's reaction.<br>
<br>
&quot;What was that spell you cast on me?&quot; she asked suddenly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Drain strength.&quot; he said, sheathing his own weapon.<br>
<br>
&quot;Drain strength? I've never seen any of the Knights use that.&quot; she said, confused.<br>
<br>
&quot;That's because paladins can't cast it.&quot; he said, clearly uncomfortable with where the conversation had led.<br>
<br>
&quot;You mean you are not a paladin?&quot; Camille began, looking at him oddly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sooo...&quot; he said, changing the subject abruptly. &quot;What brings you to the Desert of Ro this fine evening?&quot;<br>
<br>
The mention of the desert brought her mission screaming home to her. She had almost forgotten it after meeting this strange young man.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, I almost forgot!&quot; she exclaimed. &quot;Can you point me in the direction of Derv One?&quot;<br>
<br>
He frowned. &quot;What is a young girl doing crawling around the desert at this time of night looking for Derv One for?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Young KNIGHT.&quot; she corrected, miffed at his tone. &quot;And it's guild business.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, young knight, forgive me.&quot; he said, pointing slowly to her right. &quot;You were close. It's about four dunes in that direction till you will be able to see their campfire, at this time of night. But perhaps I could accompany you to...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, thank you.&quot; she said abruptly, wincing at her tone, but wanting to do this on her own. &quot;As you may have seen, I am more than capable of defending myself. Goodnight, River.&quot; And she began marching in the direction he had pointed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Just be careful, milady.&quot; he called out after her. &quot;There are strange things afoot in the desert now adays....&quot; but the last of his voice faded away as she marched on.<br>
<br>
He was correct, she was not far off. As she topped the fourth dune she saw the campfire, and upon creeping closer, the three tents surrounding it. An orc was warming his hands at the fire in the cold desert night air, but other than some movement in one of the tents, she could see no other people.<br>
<br>
The dervs were an odd bunch, appearing serveral years ago in the desert of Ro. A nomadic people, other than for a few skirmishes over market prices when they ventured close to Freeport, they generally kept to themselves. But intelligence had caught rumors that a strange darkelf from the Nektulos was travelling from camp to camp, and it was feared that an alliance of some sort was in the works. So the Knights sent out all those they had in training to watch the camps, to see if indeed this dark elf existed, or if it was just a rumor. Her assignment was Derv One, but thus far, she saw no sign of a teir'dal.<br>
<br>
Slowly she crept around the dune, attempting to get a better glimpse at the occupants of the tents.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Dunestalker...&quot; she whispered nervously, making her way down the sandy hill.<br>
<br>
The cold steel of a knife to her throat from behind and an iron grip on the back of her neck stopped her dead in her tracks.<br>
<br>
&quot;What's this, a pretty miss?&quot; came a harsh female barbarian voice from behind her. The grip tightened, and Camille's eyes watered in pain. &quot;Let's see yer weapon girlie, nice an' slow, and drop it where Weezer kin git at it.&quot; <br>
<br>
The knife at her throat decided it for Camille. She slowly drew her weapon and dropped it to the sand, where a ragged, filthy human, presumably Weezer, scooped it up and pranced, half dancing, toward the tents. The blade was removed from her throat and pressed roughly to her mailed back, and she was given a rough shove from behind.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now march, missy, or I'll skewer ya like a pig, by gods.&quot; the woman said, pushing Camille again. Camille slowly made her way towards the tents. As she passed the orc, he looked at her chest hungrily and licked his lips. The orc fell in place behind her.<br>
<br>
The flap to the largest tent was thrown to the side and she was pushed roughly inside. <br>
<br>
There, across from her, eating a leg of mutton, was a teir'dal in full armor, blinking his violet eyes in surprise.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lookit here what I found sneakin' around in the sand, Dorn.&quot; the barbarian woman said, pushing Camille forward.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, a Knight of Truth.&quot; the dark elf, Dorn said, appraising her with his eyes like one looks at a bug. &quot;They have been spotted at almost all of the camps poking around. Silly asses think it is wise to spy in full plate mail. Such noisy noisy spies.&quot; And then, his appraisal over, he went back to his mutton. &quot;Varissa, strip her out of her armor.&quot; Dorn said to the barbarian, and then indicated the orc. &quot;And the give her to Grozz to play with.&quot; The orc clapped his hands together and began unbuckling his pants, tongue licking over his lips again. &quot;If there's anything left, toss it to Weezer, is time he became a man. Then we will discuss tomorrow's caravan from Oasis, and how we may relieve Freeport's taxes that are starving your people...&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille's stood still in shock, still feeling the press of the blade to her back, as the orc's pants hit the floor with a jangle of beltstraps. Three opponents, she thought. The armor may buy me some time. Horrible odds, but if I can get a stun off...<br>
<br>
&quot;Put your clothes back on, Grozz, before you catch cold.&quot; commanded a strong voice from the entrance. It was the voice of a leader. <br>
<br>
Grozz stood blinking, pants around his ankles. Camille turned to follow his stare.<br>
<br>
There was River standing in the doorway, one hand outside the flap, the other holding his sword drawn.<br>
<br>
Dorn leapt to his feet. &quot;Do not interfere, Riverdane.&quot;, he growled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Dorn B'Dynn.&quot; he said amiably, but his eyes were not smiling. They were cold, flat, emotionless. &quot;I thought I saw you sneaking around the dunes this afternoon. What brings you crawling out from under your rock in Neriak?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dorn's hand crept toward his sword at his waist. &quot;Business from the Fatherland, human. You may think yourself protected because you bear the Taint, but if you get in my way I will not hesitate to skewer you alive!&quot;<br>
<br>
River laughed. &quot;With what? That piece of mutton?&quot; he chuckled.<br>
<br>
That was enough for Dorn. With a roar, he threw the mutton aside, and drew out his sword.<br>
<br>
&quot;Miss Stun, catch!&quot; River called, bringing his outside hand into the tent. It held Camille's weapon, wet with blood. Seeing River unmarked, she absently realized it must be Weezer's blood. She came out of her daze and caught the weapon midair.<br>
<br>
Varissa violently brought the knife at Camille's back up to her throat again, with the intent to cut her windpipe. But Camille, automatically, without so much thinking as just doing, reversed the sword as she caught it, and drove it back under her arm with both hands. She felt it slide home and then the sudden sticky wet rush of blood onto her hands. The knife at her throat fell uselessly to the ground, as Camille pushed the dying woman off her back and pulled her weapon free of her. Some part of her stomach revolted as she dimmly realized she had slain her first living person in combat, while another more primitive part of her cheered.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, Dorn had rushed River, swinging wildly up over his head. River's sheild came up, deflecting the blow, but Dorn spun, countering River's riposte and slipping out the entrance as he danced past. River turned half in the entrance and half out, furiously exchanging blows with Dorn B'Dynn outside.<br>
<br>
Grozz still stood there with his pants around his ankles, at River's back. Then, coming to his senses, he grabbed a long carving knife from Dorn's dinner table and raised it, shuffling over to where River fought. He brought it high, intent on plunging it into River's neck.<br>
<br>
&quot;River!&quot; Camille cried, eyes flashing blue.<br>
<br>
-STUN-<br>
<br>
Grozz stood poised over River, knocked senseless for a moment by the force of Camille's stun, hand still gripping the knife but unable to move.<br>
<br>
Without turning into the tent, Riverdane's hand shot back, locking around Grozz's throat. And then something...peculiar happened. Grozz's eyes bulged as all the color drained out of his face, and then his skin....collapsed, falling in upon itself as Camille watched in shock. Within seconds, nothing but an empty husk remained. River let go and Grozz's empty skin fluttered to the ground like parchment. And then, blocking a swing from Dorn, River disappeared outside as he and B'Dynn battled.<br>
<br>
Camille came out of her surprise and ran from the tent. There to the side was Weezer's body, but his head...was nowhere to be seen. Meanwhile, Riverdane and Dorn were locked in mortal combat, Dorn having produced a long parrying knife and dual weilding. River was good, but it was obvious with the way Dorn was handling his weapons that the teir'dal was the superior.<br>
<br>
Without thinking, Camille joined the fray, swinging without a word into the fight. But Dorn was good, damned good, holding Camille off with the parrying knife, as River and he exchanged blows. And then, Dorn's weapon slipped through River's defenses, cutting across the leather armor on his bicep and drawing blood in a thick line. River howled, and spun off, muttering something in a coarse language Camille did not understand.<br>
<br>
And then River's eyes pulsed green.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, in the air, tiny green skulls materialized and began to spin, as green light shot out of River's eyes and pierced Dorn's body. Camille stopped midswing, gaping, panting for air as she stared at the lightshow.<br>
<br>
Dorn dropped his weapons, screaming. But the scream was not one of pain....rather, one of terror. It went right through Camille as he turned, shrieking, and disappeared over the dunes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Dammit!&quot; River growled, touching his fingers to the slice on his arm tenderly.<br>
<br>
&quot;What did you cast on him?&quot; Camille whispered in awe.<br>
<br>
River did not meet her stare. Rather, he began slowly unbuckling the leather and peeling it away from the wound. &quot;Fear. I cast Fear.&quot; he said softly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Fear?&quot; she asked, &quot;But I thought necromancers cast fear, but you're...you're no caster.&quot; Her head was a jumble of confused questions. &quot;And what did he mean that you have the Taint?&quot;<br>
<br>
River drew his eyes away from his wound, and looked at her squarely.<br>
<br>
&quot;My mother was Eleese of the Commons.&quot; he said intensely. Camille gasped involuntarily. Every girl who had ever disobeyed their parents were warned they would end up like Crazy Eleese, Madwoman of West Commons. It was a popular tale to frighten children with, since it was true.<br>
<br>
&quot;I see you have heard of her,&quot; River continued, going on. &quot;She was raped by Innoruuk and left for dead. Dane found her and took her in. She gave birth to me. That...is the Taint. I am born of a mad woman and the seed of Innoruuk.&quot; He reached out, grabbing her hand, wanting desperately for her to understand. She felt she should recoil, but somehow, could not. &quot;That is why I can never join your Knights of Truth. That is why I can not learn the magic of healing, or stuns, or the rest of the code. I will never be a paladin, Camille. I am a shadowknight, the only thing I could be.&quot; He then suddenly brought her hand up to his lips, kissing the back of her hand, and glancing up at her sidelong. &quot;But I'm not that bad.&quot; he grinned, and released her hand, starting off for the dunes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Fear doesn't last long, milady!&quot; he called back to her. &quot;I would be off before Dorn returns!&quot; And then, the dunes obscured him from view, while she stood dazed looking out after where he had disappeared.<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Wyldechylde...&quot; she whispered softly, and then, clearing her head, made her way away from the camp.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 381<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/8/03 3:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Camille awoke suddenly, body stiff. She blinked twice in surprise, not quite sure where she was. Pale light lit the stable, as she realized she was laying on a pile of hay. My gods, she thought, I slept till dawn. The memory of the dream was quickly escaping her the way dreams do, and she felt a pang of loss as the recollection of her first meeting River slowly faded away. It wasn't without its bad parts, the dream, but when his lips had touched her hand...<br>
<br>
She suddenly realized she was not alone in the stable. Grelin sat on his haunches, a silly grin on his face, watching her. When her eyes met his, he smiled wider, stood, and ran out of the stables. She rose, groaning to her feet. Brimstone was no where to be seen. Reaver was still gripped in her hand. With horror she noticed that it was covered in blood, as was the hay where it had laid.<br>
<br>
Grelin returned, with Rocsalt in tow. And slowing, limping severely, Talvarien entered the stable behind them, eyeing Camille warily and giving her a large berth.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm sorry if I worried you, guys.&quot; Camille began, stepping forward. Talvarien scuttled backwards, terror in his eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Cami,&quot; he said, panic in his voice. &quot;Put DOWN the sword!Down girl! Don't hurt the Talv....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Huh?&quot; she asked, confusion in her eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Before Talvarien has an accident in his pants, I suggest you put down the sword, Cami.&quot; Roc suggested. &quot;He's already had enough for one day.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't understand,&quot; Camille said.<br>
<br>
&quot;You stabbed him.&quot; Grelin grinned.<br>
<br>
&quot;I WHAT?&quot; Camille said in shock, stepping towards Talvarien.<br>
<br>
&quot;DON'T HURT ME!&quot; Talv half-shrieked, pulling Rocsalt in front of him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Talv!&quot; Camille said, slowly placing the bloody sword onto the ground. &quot;I'm sorry...I....what happened??&quot; She took two steps deliberately away from the sword.<br>
<br>
&quot;When we woke up and you missed breakfast, we started looking for you.&quot; Roc said. &quot;Talv tracked you to the stable, found you sleeping in the hay. He tried to wake you up.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And you tried to KILL me like a crazy woman!&quot; Talv wailed. &quot;Where's the love? None!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You sliced him in the leg, without even opening your eyes. And then you went right on sleeping.&quot; Rocsalt said, with a half smile. &quot;He screamed like a little girl.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It HURT!&quot; Talv exclaimed indignantly. &quot;It took three ranja heals to stop me from bleeding to death.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Bah.&quot; Roc said. &quot;It takes a full ranger heal to heal a mosquito bite. You were fine after Grelin popped a regen on you. And what's with the limp?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll be a gimp for life.&quot; Talvarien predicted.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're gimp now.&quot; Grelin replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;No love!&quot; Talvarien exclaimed, and was silent.<br>
<br>
&quot;Talv, I'm sorry, I didn't know what I was doing.&quot; Camille apologized sincerely. &quot;I've had a....long night. And long day it seems. I missed breakfast? That means...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye,&quot; Roc finished for her. &quot;It's sunset now. You slept the whole day away.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The whole day.&quot; Camille said, agitated. River was locked in that gem, and she was sleeping away what could be precious time. &quot;Let's get back to the guildhouse, guys. I need to get into some clothes and tell you what happened.&quot;<br>
<br>
She picked up Reaver, and left towards the house, Rocsalt and Grelin at her side. Talvarien fell into step behind them, with a careful eye on Camille's swordhand, but the limp miraculously gone. He was as curious as the other two to where Brimstone had gone and why Camille was asleep in the stables.<br>
<br>
Grelin fixed a quick dinner as Camille detailed her meeting with Terris, the history of Grieg, the use of the blue gem, every little detail she could remember. They ate quietly while she told the tale, stopping every now and then to eat. She was ravenous. At the end she sat back, exhausted by the retelling.<br>
<br>
&quot;So what do we do now, head over to Greig's place and bust River out, powpowpowpow?&quot; Talvarien said, all thoughts of his little injury forgotten.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; Grelin said, shaking his head.<br>
<br>
&quot;You remember what Katarin said about that statue.&quot; Rocsalt added. &quot;Akethadar couldn't scratch it. It would be suicide to head in there just us four.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Plus Terris wanted me to talk to Vven first.&quot; Camille said, recalling how insistant the goddess had been. &quot;He may have some answers for us that will make some sense.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I haven't seen Vven Psyphon since.....since my arms got ripped off and they buried me during End Game.&quot; Talvarien said with a shudder.<br>
<br>
&quot;He stayed on in Hate, taking my place when Innoruuk demanded a soul be paid.&quot; Camille said, remembering back two years ago. &quot;I bet he is still there.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then we need to get to Hate.&quot; Roc said, standing up. &quot;Which means...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We need a wizard.&quot; Camille finished. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 382<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/8/03 2:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> &quot;Verdad, let us in!&quot; Camille called again, knocking on the door urgently.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not home?&quot; Grelin suggested.<br>
<br>
&quot;He's home, I see candlelight in the windows.&quot; Camille said, knocking again. &quot;My mother was a wizard, she would never leave a lit fire in the house if her and my father were out. Wizards respect the power of fire too much.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Allow me.&quot; Rocsalt said, stepping forward. He rapped his knuckles on the door, hard.<br>
<br>
Inside, the sound of a door opening hastily, and then the locks clicking open. The door swung open.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come in, A....&quot; Verdad began, standing in the doorway in nothing but black boxers decorated in bright red hearts. A half finished bottle of wine was in one hand. As he took in the four in his doorway, his mouth dropped open in surprise.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry to call this late, Verd.&quot; Camille apologized, &quot;But I need a favor.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, bad time guys....&quot; Verdad began, finding his voice, turning his head to a closed door behind him nervously. The sound of falling water stopped, and Verdad looked back at them imploringly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nice duds. Is that real silk?&quot; Talvarien said, slipping past Verdad into the room. Verdad turned with him, panic in his eyes, as the rest filed into the room. &quot;Wowowow, look at this place!&quot; Talvarien exclaimed, taking in the lush couch, with the candelabras lit in all corners, half eaten cheese platter on the marble table, plush tigerskin rug. Outer clothing was scattered all over the couch, some male, some female. &quot;Is this an original?&quot; he asked, pointing to a satyr and nymph orgy scene framed on the wall.<br>
<br>
Verdad quickly closed the door behind them as they invaded his living room. &quot;Cami, heh, I would never close my door to you, I hope you know that, but your timing is a little....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Verd, I wouldn't have come if it weren't important.&quot; Camille said honestly. But Verdad was only half listening, still looking at the door from which the sound of water had stopped.<br>
<br>
&quot;Any other time, ok?&quot; Verdad begged.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good cheese!&quot; Talvarien said, popping another piece in his mouth.<br>
<br>
&quot;I need to get to Hate.&quot; Camille said quickly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hate?&quot; Verdad blinked. &quot;Just get on that horse of River's. You still have it, don't you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Suddenly the door swung open, and a redheaded highelf, dressed only a towel, walked out, facedown as she wrapped up her hair in another towel, water dripping onto the carpet.<br>
<br>
&quot;So where is this surprise you promi...&quot; she began, looking up. And then her mouth dropped open as she took in the room.<br>
<br>
&quot;Jazzy...&quot; Verdad began, hands up in supplication as her face grew dark.<br>
<br>
&quot;THIS is the surprise?&quot; she exclaimed indignantly, anger rising. &quot;FOUR PEOPLE??&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We lost the horse.&quot; Talvarien answered for Camille obliviously, popping another piece of cheese into his mouth.<br>
<br>
&quot;HORSE??&quot; Jazzy shrieked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Jazzy it's not what it seems...&quot; Verdad began, face crumbling.<br>
<br>
But she was not listening. She stalked over to the couch and grabbed up her robes. &quot;You sick perverted...&quot; and a string of colorful curses as she stormed into the bathroom and slammed the door behind her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry, Verdad.&quot; Camille said, mortified. <br>
<br>
&quot;You're cramping my style!&quot; Verdad wailed, and then a knock on the door. Verdad's eyes went wild. &quot;Don't get...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I got it.&quot; Talv said blithely, swinging open the door.<br>
<br>
In the doorway, another, younger high elven girl stood with her eyes closed, wearing a long black trenchcoat. The moment the door swung open, she opened the trenchcoat wide with a smile. Underneath she was wearing two tassels, a skimpy loin cloth and.....nothing else.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wore it!&quot; she said brightly, eyes still closed. &quot;Where's my surprise??&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Surprise.&quot; Grelin said, grinning.<br>
<br>
The girl's eyes snapped open.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aiene....&quot; Verdad began.<br>
<br>
&quot;Impressive.&quot; Rocsalt commented, eyebrows raised, as Aiene hastily covered herself with the trenchcoat.<br>
<br>
&quot;There's no horse!&quot; Talvarien added emphatically.<br>
<br>
Aiene screamed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aiene...&quot; Verdad tried again, when Jazzy swung open the bathroom door, now fully dressed, and took in the latest addition in shock.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh my gods, you sick bastard!&quot; Jazzy exclaimed. &quot;Aiene too? She's only seventeen!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Today's my birthday.&quot; Aiene said miserably.<br>
<br>
&quot;She's legal now!&quot; Verdad tried desperately.<br>
<br>
&quot;And there's NO horse! None!&quot; Talvarien piped up helpfully.<br>
<br>
&quot;Perverts!&quot; Jazzy exclaimed, shooting Verdad a murderous look. He took a tentative step toward her, but her eyes narrowed and she disappeared from view, gating.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aiene...&quot; Verdad sighed, turning back to the girl in his doorway. She was fuming.<br>
<br>
&quot;YOU RUINED MY BIRTHDAY!&quot; she screamed, eyes lighting gold. A white hammer materialized in the air, hovering for a moment.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not in the face!&quot; Verdad cried, as the hammer flew at him. He ducked.<br>
<br>
--SMASH-- the hammer hit Talvarien full in the face, breaking his nose.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ranja...down...&quot; Talvarien said weakly, slumping onto the couch.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aiene...&quot; Verdad tried again, but the girl blinked, and like Jazzy, gated.<br>
<br>
&quot;Verdad...&quot; Camille began lamely.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're KILLING me here, Cami!&quot; Verdad growled, looking distraught in his boxers.<br>
<br>
&quot;Verd, I wouldn't have come if this wasn't important!&quot; Camille pleaded. &quot;It's about River...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;River is dead, Cami,&quot; Verdad said, miffed. &quot;As I have been trying to remind you for the last six months...&quot; He suddenly tapered off, a nervous look crossing his face. &quot;Um, he IS dead, right?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes and no...&quot; Camille began.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah dammit, Grelin, fix Talv's nose!&quot; Verdad exclaimed, noticing the ranjer groaning behind him. &quot;He's bleeding all over the damned couch...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Easy with the schnozz!&quot; Talvarien yelped, as Grelin touched his fingers, glowing green, to Talvarien's shattered nose.<br>
<br>
&quot;So what exactly did you wreck my life for?&quot; Verdad asked, shrugging into a robe and sinking into an easy chair.<br>
<br>
And Camille, for the second time that night, told her tale. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 385<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/8/03 7:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> &quot;This is unreal.&quot; Verdad commented, staring at Camille when she finished.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's real alright, Verd.&quot; Camille replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;You know,&quot; Verdad said, &quot;It's getting to the point where I'm afraid when I see a Wyldechylde.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Will you help?&quot; Camille asked, looking him in the eye.<br>
<br>
&quot;On one condition.&quot; Verdad said.<br>
<br>
&quot;And that is?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dinner when this is over.&quot; Verdad said, watching her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not a chance.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, I'll do it anyway.&quot; Verdad sighed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you, Verd.&quot; Camille smiled. &quot;We need to leave at once.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, stone please.&quot; Verdad said, standing up.<br>
<br>
&quot;Stone?&quot; Camille said blankly.<br>
<br>
Verdad sighed. &quot;Hate stone. I need a reagent to port.&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille looked flustered, and glanced around at the lost looks of her companions. &quot;I...err..don't....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You didn't bring a rock.&quot; Verdad finished for her. &quot;Ok, buckle up, we're headed to the Nektulos. I need to see a guy River turned me on to that can work the inside.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Nektulos?&quot; Camille asked, confused.<br>
<br>
&quot;The only place port stone to Hate are sold are in Neriak. There's a guy I use in there for potions and other oddities.&quot; And then, with a word in elvish, they shimmered and disappeared.<br>
<br>
With a flash of light, they found themselves on the flat-topped pyramid that was the wizard portal in the Nektulos Forest, which housed the teir'dal city of Neriak. Verdad started off, motioning for them to stay.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll be back in about ten minutes.&quot; he said over his shoulder.<br>
<br>
Talvarien glanced down at the ground and then looked up. &quot;Verd waitwaitwait.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What?&quot; Verdad asked, stopping impatiently.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm picking up....&quot; Talvarien began, running down the side of the pyramid and staring at the grass. &quot;One two three...ten...twenty? More. Over twenty guards in full armor near here, and not long ago either.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Over twenty guards?&quot; Verdad said incredulously. Not that he didn't believe him. They may be correct in doubting Talvarien could tie his boots without hurting himself, but when it came to tracking, they trusted the ranger's talents implicitly. It was just that large a force in the Nektulos was unheard of for a very long time.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye.&quot; Talv said, looking up, &quot;And they're patrolling. They'll be back.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, I can send you all back to my place....&quot; Verdad began.<br>
<br>
&quot;We'll go with you.&quot; Camille suggested. &quot;Grelin, Spirit of Eagle and Foilage Sheild please.&quot;<br>
<br>
Grelin nodded and began chanting. His first spell lifted them up in the air, levitating them, lending speed to their movement, and blessed their eyes to see the invisible. The second spell made them disappear from normal sight, though they all saw each other plainly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alright, while it holds.&quot; Verdad said, &quot;Let's move.&quot;<br>
<br>
They made their way double quick through the forest to the city of Neriak. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 387<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/9/03 11:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Verdad turned to them outside the filthy hut deep in Neriak's Foreign Quarter, and mouthed, This is it. Camille nodded, and followed Verdad into the rundown shack, the others on her heels.<br>
<br>
She stopped dead as a dog began to growl.<br>
<br>
And then a loud whipcrack as something in the shadows passed wind.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shhhh, Stinky!&quot; a decrepid voice called out from the gloom across the room. &quot;Don't growl at the dinner guests! Kekkekekkekkekekke!&quot;<br>
<br>
The dog's growl tapered off to a low snarl, but didn't stop.<br>
<br>
&quot;Soso?&quot; the voice asked, &quot;Who be here? Sound off, cause I can't see you yet!&quot;<br>
<br>
Verdad murmured something, and his hand began to glow with wizardfire, just enough to light the room for Camille and Rocsalt, his two human companions, with their weaker eyes.<br>
<br>
Across from them, sitting in the darkness stirring a large soup pot, was a disgusting troll. A filthy cur of a dog lay at his feet, hackles raised, looking at them dangerously.<br>
<br>
&quot;We see you now, Scurg.&quot; Verdad said, addressing the troll.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah you see me, but I don't see you, see? Kekekekkekk! Soup needed radishes!&quot; the troll laughed oddly, pointing up to his face. Both eyes were missing, leaving nothing but dark black holes in his face.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm so going to be sick.&quot; Talvarien moaned.<br>
<br>
&quot;If you do, do it in the pot!&quot; Scurg suggested. &quot;So, I hear two. One voice I know, one I don't. But there are more yes? I hear your in out of breath! So who be you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Camille Wyldechylde.&quot; Camille offered, trying not to breathe in the stench.<br>
<br>
&quot;Talvarien.&quot; Talv said, shifting uncomfortably.<br>
<br>
&quot;Rocsalt. Di'Varr.&quot; Roc added, and able to finally make noise after their hushed trip through the city's outskirts, let go with his cough he had been surpressing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Grelin.&quot; the druid finished.<br>
<br>
&quot;Five! Old Scurg has five bless me, come to my home! Going to need more soup!&quot; Then he turned roughly in Verdad's direction. &quot;So, back so soon, paleface? Ran out of Scurg's Spirit of Rabbit already? Lady friends like it, yes? Thumpthumpthumpthump done!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Err...&quot; Verdad said, face turning red. &quot;I don't need any more potions, Scurg, thanks, I need...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, I know what you need.&quot; Scurg murmured, stirring his pot. &quot;Scurg know lots of things.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I know Scurg is out of his freakin' gourd.&quot; Talvarien whispered to Rocsalt.<br>
<br>
&quot;Kekekkkkekekkk, ranger boy!&quot; Scurg said loudly, turning his eyeless face directly to Talvarien. &quot;I threw my eyes into the soup, but not my ears! You may be right, you may be right, but it better to listen to a crazy man than to hear nothing at all, yesyes?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, yeah.&quot; Talvarien said, embarrassed he had been heard.<br>
<br>
Scurg continued to stir his pot. &quot;Yesyes, Scurg hear many things. Scurg see many thing, with or without radishes! Scurg see snakes slither across the face of the moon! Scurg smell a change in the wind!&quot; And to punctuate that, he farted loudly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Scurg,&quot; Verdad said suddenly. &quot;There is increased patrols in the Nektulos. You know anything about that?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ahh, the darkies are up in arms!&quot; Scurg gibbered, nodding. All cities are increasing their watches! Something strange afoot, for lighties and darkies both! The books of passage are gone, poof, stolen!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Books of passage?&quot; Rocsalt asked. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, sick one.&quot; Scurg said, turning in Rocsalt's direction. Roc gave another involuntary cough, almost on cue. Camille glanced at him nervously before looking back to the troll.<br>
<br>
&quot;What books of passage?&quot; Camille asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;He means the portal books to Plane of Knowledge,&quot; Verdad said slowly. &quot;Don't you, Scurg?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yesyes,&quot; Scurg said, nodding vigorously, &quot;Young lion smart as he is virile! Kekkekekkkekekke!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What the hells?&quot; Verdad asked. &quot;Those books are fused to the pedestals they sit upon, to prevent theft.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But when the rock become soup, easy enough to pluck out the chicken!&quot; Scurg chortled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Rock becomes soup?&quot; Verdad asked, confused.<br>
<br>
&quot;Whoever take the books, melted the rock!&quot; Scurg informed him, stirring the pot happily.<br>
<br>
&quot;Odd.&quot; Rocsalt commented.<br>
<br>
&quot;Great.&quot; Verdad moaned, looking at Grelin. &quot;Well, Grel, get ready for a ton of 'Hey dood, can you port to West Commons for 5 plat?'...&quot; Grelin nodded sadly. &quot;So, Scurg, I need a Hate rock.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, going up to see my old friend, aye? Tell him for Scurg things too quiet around here without him! Kekekekkkekke!&quot; Then Scurg reached down under his seat, looking for something. &quot;Hate stone, Hate stone...&quot; he murmured. &quot;Ah, here it be!&quot; And he withdrew something from under his chair and held it in Talvarien's general direction. It was a lumpy shape, brown, and had a foul odor. Talvarien took it from the troll and stared at it, holding it in his hand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, Scurg.&quot; Verdad said, &quot;That's not a Hate stone.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hmm?&quot; Scurg asked, snatching it back from Talvarien. He sniffed it once. &quot;So it ain't! Bad dog!&quot; he scolded, as the dog cringed. &quot;Bad Stinky! I told you, not in the house!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Gah!&quot; Talvarien exclaimed in disgust, frantically wiping his hands on his leggings.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah well, flavor for soup!&quot; Scurg said, tossing the dog turd into the pot with a wet splash. &quot;Now where be it?&quot; and he went rummaging under hs chair again. After a short time, he brought up a black stone, looking very much like coal.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah here it be, yes?&quot; Scurg said, holding it out.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not touching it!&quot; Talvarien cried.<br>
<br>
&quot;That's it, Scurg, thanks.&quot; Verdad said, taking the stone from the troll. &quot;Put it on my tab.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That I will, that I will, kekekekekke.&quot; the troll chuckled. &quot;So....stay for dinner?&quot; he pointed to the pot.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll pass.&quot; Talvarien said weakly, still wiping his hands.<br>
<br>
&quot;We have to go, Scurg.&quot; Camille said politely, &quot;But thank you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ahh, another time, maybe!&quot; Scurg suggested brightly. Then he stared in Camille's direction. &quot;Give Scurg some time with Mithaniel's handmaiden, yesyes? I have secrets for her.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; Grelin and Rocsalt said in unison.<br>
<br>
Camille blinked, hearing herself addressed by the strange troll in what she had thought to be a semi-private name for her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Guys, I'll be fine.&quot; she said slowly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Cami...&quot; Rocsalt began.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you doubt my ability to fight, Roc? Or am I just River's wife to you?&quot; she said warningly, looking at him with an eyebrow raised. Rocsalt's mouth snapped shut and he said nothing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Leave us a moment, I'll be right out.&quot; she said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gladly.&quot; Talvarien said, slipping out the front door.<br>
<br>
&quot;Be quick Cami.&quot; Verdad said, &quot;We'll be between the huts outside. We shouldn't be seen by the guards in this area.&quot;<br>
<br>
And, with a last look of disapproval from Grelin and Rocsalt, the men made their way outside.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come closer, dreamer.&quot; Scurg chortled, stirring the soup. Camille obliged him and came closer to the blind troll.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, like a snake, he dropped his ladle into the soup and grabbed her right hand in both of hers. His grip was clammy but firm. Her first reaction was to strike him, but she kept that in check, as his grip was not for pain, but to emphasize his next speech.<br>
<br>
&quot;Remember this, girlie!&quot; the troll whispered, his face up close a picture of madness. &quot;When you want to talk to the dead, they got no ears left when the worms finish with them! So, you wanna talk to the dead, you gotta speak their language! They say dead men tell no tales, but dead women got plenty to say! Heed the troll shammie! Scurg knows many things! And the Dane still got plenty to say, for a man with no tongue! Kekekkkekkkekekekkekekeke!&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille, body recoiling from his insane chatter, yanked her hand out of his grasp.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you...&quot; she managed, making her way out the door, trying to make sense of his gibberish.<br>
<br>
&quot;Anytime, girlie!&quot; Scurg called out after her, &quot;And when it's all done, come for soup!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ready?&quot; Verdad said, seeing Camille appear in the alley.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye.&quot; she said.<br>
<br>
&quot;What did that crazy bastard say to you?&quot; Talvarien asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Later.&quot; Camille said distractedly, rubbing her hand absently where the troll had touched her, trying to get the clammy feeling out of her system.<br>
<br>
&quot;Be ready for anything.&quot; Verdad warned. &quot;I hear Hate has changed a bit.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I love the place.&quot; Rocsalt said. &quot;I spent so many raids there I could pull it blindfolded.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not anymore.&quot; Verdad corrected him, starting to chant.<br>
<br>
&quot;Huh?&quot; Rocsalt began.<br>
<br>
But then, the incantation done, they winked out of sight, as the slums of Neriak disappeared from around them.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 388<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/9/03 1:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Hate had....changed.<br>
<br>
They appeared around a shallow well, one Camille had never seen before in her previous raids on the home of Innoruuk. Normally you would arrive in Hate in a small abandoned building, praying that you wouldn't be swarmed by patrolling mobs that milled without direction through the streets. Now, you were outside on the streets in a corner, with no instant flurry of action, since the streets were deserted.<br>
<br>
&quot;They removed the second floor.&quot; Rocsalt commented, glancing up. Camille followed his gaze. The low ceiling of the plane of Hate had disappeared, and the gothic buildings soared into the heights, arched and majestic, the architecture impressive in the pale blue glow that seemed to light the plane.<br>
<br>
&quot;So, the reports were right.&quot; Verdad said. &quot;Zone in is safe....&quot;<br>
<br>
Talvarien was inspecting the walls surrounding the well with interest, reaching out to touch the bricks. &quot;Wowowow, look at the stonework on this wa...&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Who dares invade the home of Innoruuk?&quot; a spite golem growled from somewhere on the other side of the wall.<br>
<br>
&quot;More victims for the Father!&quot; cackled an unseen loathesome lich.<br>
<br>
&quot;Blerg blerg!&quot; cried an evil little imp.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ooops?&quot; Talvarien said lamely.<br>
<br>
&quot;Same old aggro problems.&quot; Rocsalt sighed. He took a defensive posture as Camille drew Reaver out of its scabbard and prepared.<br>
<br>
From around the corner came a crowd of Hate's denizens.<br>
<br>
&quot;So not good....&quot; Talvarien said nervously, drawing his bow.<br>
<br>
&quot;No chanters, I'm using areas...&quot; Verdad murmured, hands glowing. Grelin looked around helplessly at the dead end they were trapped in.<br>
<br>
&quot;Succor no good.&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; Verdad agreed. &quot;Probably drop us off right here again.&quot;<br>
<br>
Surrounded, the mob of liches, revenants, clerics, and other nightmares came towards them.<br>
<br>
&quot;Cami! Verd!&quot; came a loud happy voice from the back. The rush of demons stopped as if frozen in place. &quot;Back, back to your camps, idiots!&quot; the voice continued, as someone began to move through the crowd. &quot;They're with me.&quot;<br>
<br>
The crowd of mobs parted, and out came a teir'dal with jet black hair and a big smile. He was carrying a clipboard and quill.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, I'll be damned!&quot; the dark elf said. &quot;Why the hells didn't you write you were coming?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Nice timing, Vven.&quot; Verdad replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's all about the timing.&quot; Vven agreed, looking from Verdad to Cami. &quot;Cami, looking wonderful, amazing what a month asleep in Hate can do for the skin....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you, Vven.&quot; Camille said, smiling despite herself.<br>
<br>
&quot;And is that Talvarien? With ARMS?&quot; Vven exclaimed. &quot;I almost didn't recognize you!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hi Vven.&quot; Talvarien said, wincing at the recollection of having his arms ripped off in the Plane of Nightmare.<br>
<br>
&quot;And Rocsalt, Grelin....&quot; Vven nodded. &quot;What, is Razor's Edge coming up for a raid? We're not open yet...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Razor disbanded after River died, Vven...&quot; Camille said quietly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, I had heard River slipped in Velks.&quot; Vven said carefully. &quot;I would have come to the funeral, but I didn't think dancing on his grave would be appropriate...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You wouldn't have danced on his grave.&quot; Camille said, not believing the teir'dal for a minute.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, maybe just a LITTLE dance....&quot; Vven laughed. &quot;Boy was Inny upset when River didn't end up here...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You look well, Vven.&quot; Camille said, changing subjects.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hate has been good for inky.&quot; Vven agreed. &quot;I found my true calling, as an administrator here. So what do you think of the place? All my idea...&quot; He turned and gestured broadly to the buildings behind him with the clipboard. &quot;Hate 2.0!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Interesting...&quot; Roc commented, face not registering if he cared for the changes or not.<br>
<br>
&quot;Vven, I came up here to talk to you about something....&quot; Camille began.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sure sure...&quot; Vven said, taking her by the hand and pulling her away from the well. &quot;Let's talk in the lounge. I can give you the nickel tour as we head over.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hate has a lounge?&quot; Rocsalt asked, nose wrinkling.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, Hate has a lot of new things.&quot; Vven said, looking at him sidelong slyly.<br>
<br>
And, as the others following the teir'dal and Camille, they made their way south into the streets of Hate. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 389<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/9/03 4:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> &quot;This first part of Hate is the same 'ole, same 'ole.&quot; Vven said, pointing to various buildings with the quill. &quot;Just with better scenery. You like it? Sorta like Katta without the fog machine.&quot; <br>
<br>
Various mobs were working their way in and out of the buildings, dragging in furniture, removing large sacks of trash, typical construction site. They paused for a moment as a spite golem crossed their path, pushing a large harpsichord into a nearby building. <br>
<br>
&quot;ANOTHER piano?&quot; Vven asked the spite golem incredulously. <br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry, Boss.&quot; the spite said apologetically. &quot;Maestro's orders.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Soooo old school.&quot; Vven sighed, steering them around the musical instrument. Then in a low whisper he added, &quot;Maestro has been pitching a fit ever since I took over operations in southern Hate. So since he was assigned Zone In, every other building has a freakin' piano. Ridiculous waste of money. What are we going to do, play classical music and BORE them to death?&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille just shrugged, not knowing quite what to say.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, so, here's Northern Hate, clerics here, spites there, yadda yadda...&quot; Vven said dismissively. &quot;Now, we're getting near my area. Cami, do you remember way back when, why Innoruuk didn't want to keep River in Hate?&quot;<br>
<br>
The answer was on her lips in a second. She still remembered the day she woke up from her long sleep in End Game like it was yesterday. &quot;He said because River would turn Hate into an amusement park.&quot; she recalled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Right!&quot; Vven exclaimed, moving them along. &quot;So after you two left, I started thinking, Hmm, not a bad idea. Took me half a year driving Inny crazy but...&quot; He turned the corner and made a grand gesture. &quot;Voila!&quot;<br>
<br>
They stopped dead in their tracks and gaped.<br>
<br>
There, sprawled out before them, lights flashing, was a huge demonic....carnival. Booths lined the streets, with dozens of games. A rollercoaster roared in the distance. Ramps leading to different attractions were everywhere, complete with rulers protruding from the ground with height requirements for certain rides.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh...my...gods...&quot; Roc blinked in disgust, and started coughing.<br>
<br>
&quot;You like it??&quot; Vven asked happily, clapping his hands together. Fortunately, Roc at the moment could not respond.<br>
<br>
An abhorrant, stone wings flapping, flew up to Vven carrying a large box. &quot;The advertisments are in, Boss!&quot; the abhorrant exclaimed.<br>
<br>
Vven excused himself for a moment while they stared at the glitzy travesty before them and took one of the fliers out of the box. As he skimmed it, his face grew dark.<br>
<br>
&quot;What the hells is this? 'Come to 'isnnyland!'....'ISNNYLAND?&quot; he barked. He rolled up the flier and rapped the abhorrant over the head with it. &quot;Idiot, do you even proofread this crap before you send it out? It's INNY'S LAND, not 'isnnyland, you moron! Get this back to the printers before they close!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes Boss.&quot; the abhorrant said miserably, lugging the box back the way he came.<br>
<br>
&quot;Can't find good help nowadays.&quot; Vven sighed, looking at them apologetically. &quot;Anyway, come, I'll show you some of the highlights!&quot;<br>
<br>
They followed him mutely, too amazed to say anything.<br>
<br>
&quot;The whole thing, you know, came to me in a flash. I mean, when I was adventuring with the rest of you saps down on Norrath, I used to think 'and THIS is what I get? Camp the Arch Mage in Guk for 8 hours for these crappy PANTS?'...risk vs. reward was more imbalanced than casters vs. melee in the Arena. Why bother? So, I figure, after you battle it out in Maestro's area, read:RISK, then you get to inky's area, read:REWARD.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh my gods, I LOVE this!&quot; Talvarien exclaimed. Rocsalt just stared at him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok ok ok,&quot; Vven said, speaking at a fast clip. &quot;Over there you got the Pirates of Guntrak, over here you have Tolapmuj's Wild Ride, and heh here's a little game I had dedicated to Whizbang, that little punk.&quot; He steered them towards a booth with a board on it, with about half a dozen holes cut into it. Chained to the board on a long cord was a fist sized replica of Pedi, Whizbang's wife. A large sign over the booth indicated the name of the game: Whack-A-Gnome.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hehh,&quot; Verdad said. &quot;I like this one.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Guarunteed to be a hit!&quot; Vven exclaimed proudly. &quot;Pop in a plat, and a little Whizbang pops out of anyone of these holes for a few seconds. The more Whizbangs you bonk with the Pedi Hammer here, the more tickets you get, till you win an Inny Doll! Whiz even goes 'Damnation!' when you hit him. Priceless!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Can I play now?&quot; Verdad asked hopefully.<br>
<br>
&quot;Later!&quot; Vven said, pulling Cami and the rest deeper into the carnival. &quot;I want to show you my biggest brainchild!&quot;<br>
<br>
They paused as a new sign loomed. In large pink letters, they read 'END GAME GROVE'.<br>
<br>
&quot;...'End Game Grove' ..???&quot; Camille exclaimed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey!&quot; Vven replied. &quot;I had some of my best laughs during End Game! So I dedicated a whole section of the park to it. Come, look!&quot;<br>
<br>
They walked under the sign, Camille still shaking her head, after Vven.<br>
<br>
In one section they found a rather large booth. On the counter, was mock pieces of a human being. Inside the booth sat a sad looking squid, dressed rather pathetically in a dragon costume. An ire ghast in a carnival barker's hat was sitting on a stool outside it. The sign over the booth read 'STARVE WUOSHI'.<br>
<br>
&quot;Starve Wuoshi!&quot; Talvarien replied in delight.<br>
<br>
&quot;That's right kid, Starve Wuoshi!&quot; the ire ghast piped up, sensing a customer. &quot;Just 5 plat to try your luck! The object is to pick up these pieces of human meat and toss them past old Wuoshi there! If you can get three body parts past her without her catching and eating them, you can get this genuine imitation Shattered Emerald of Corruption, just like all the rangers want!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Imitation?&quot; Talvarien asked, smile fading. &quot;Doesn't the real Shattered Emerald of Corruption drop in Hate?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hheh, yeah kid,&quot; the ghast chuckled, rolling his eyes. &quot;Surrre it does.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hard as hells to win too!&quot; Vven added. &quot;See our Wuoshi there? Out of work squid-thing from the Plane of Water. Not much to look at, but the damned things got sixteen arms! Nothing gets past him!&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille took a good look at the pieces of 'human' on the counter. Her eyes came to rest on the head. Something about it was familiar. Long black hair, moustache....<br>
<br>
&quot;Vven!&quot; she shrieked.<br>
<br>
&quot;What??&quot; he asked, recoiling from the anger in her voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are feeding this Wuoshi thing a dummy of RIVER?&quot; she yelled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok ok ok! Poor taste!&quot; Vven said as she bonked him. &quot;I'll have it changed to Verdad or something!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You better...&quot; Camille warned.<br>
<br>
&quot;Take a picture with Ramluk?&quot; Vven said, trying to lead them away from the replica of Riverdane's dismembered body. A large spite golem in ogre battle armor stood looking bored against a pole.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ogre.&quot; it said half-heartedly.<br>
<br>
&quot;That's OGGA!,&quot; Vven whispered fiercely, jabbing the thing in its side. &quot;You're making me look bad!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ogga.&quot; it said, shrugging its massive shoulders.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok ok ok.&quot; Vven said, eyes murderous, pulling them in yet another direction. &quot;This one's my favorite. Check this out!&quot; He dragged them to a large mechanical model, rather realistically rendered of a large tree, with the features of a beautiful elven woman etched into the bark. Above it, was a pretty sign that said 'The Tunare Tree'.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, stand back!&quot; he said, as a forsaken revenant ran up to him with a bottle of liquor and a torch. Vven took both and stood in front of the tree.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, I learned this trick from an old friend Momur....that chick makes me look like an amateur.&quot; And with that he took a huge swig of alcohol, holding it in his mouth. Then he quickly brought the torch near his face, and with a woooosh spit out the drink into the fire. A huge flame shot from his mouth, hitting the tree and enveloping it in fire.<br>
<br>
Immediately, two eyes in the tree opened up as it started to burn. The woman's mouth started opening and closing as the branches began flailing about. &quot;Oh no!&quot; she wailed. &quot;It's End Game! I'm burning! I'm burninggg!&quot;<br>
<br>
Vven wiped his mouth and stood back proudly. &quot;Gods I love that.&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille addressed the demented dark elf from a distance. &quot;Vven, this is...fascinating. But we really need to talk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok ok ok.&quot; Vven said, steering them away from the tree, which was still moaning something about 'The tear! The tear!'. &quot;Let's hit the bar.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;A bar in Hate.&quot; Rocsalt murmured.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah!&quot; Vven said, stopping in front of a large building. &quot;Here it is.&quot; A large sign above named the bar. It said: JEERS.<br>
<br>
Vven pushed his way in. The place was packed with undead, drinking and having a rather good time. When he entered, they all lifted their mugs of beer as one. &quot;Vven!&quot; they chorused.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey.&quot; he waved, then turned to his companions. &quot;Where everybody knows your name.&quot; he said, motioning to a large unoccupied table to the side.<br>
<br>
Sitting down, Vven finally slowed down, and looked at Cami.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, Cam. What do you want to talk about?&quot; he asked.<br>
<br>
Cami took a deep breath, and said, &quot;What do you know about Greig Veneficus?&quot;<br>
<br>
Vven's blue skin drained almost of all color.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh boy. There's a name I try not to think about.&quot; he said, twitching nervously.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tell me.&quot; Camille insisted.<br>
<br>
And he did.<br>
