<br>
&quot;For Hand of Virtue for you and Pedi's anniversary.&quot; Talvarien finished, nodding. Whizbang favored him with a scowl.<br>
<br>
&quot;Would you like to finish the story, ranger?&quot; he growled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shutting up!&quot; Talvarien said hastily.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good. For Hand of Virtue for Pedi for our anniversary.&quot; Whiz continued on. &quot;Typical day in the Bazaar. People are selling every piece of junk they could find in their neighbor's garbage. And its slow,, everyone is selling, no one is buying. To make matters worse, my stall location is right on top of the stables, so I get to listen to those idiot casino people while smelling horse crap all day. This is doing nothing to improve my mood.<br>
<br>
On top of it, it's hot and getting hotter. I don't ever recall it being that hot in the Bazaar, and I've been there when it was packed to capacity. It's like all the air vents intot the place were blocked or something, no ventilation at all. So I'm starting to sweat, the casino people are driving me nuts with their ridiculous odds and non-stop pitches, and I'm gagging as the heat is doing wonders for the horse crap....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So you blew up the Bazaar!&quot; Talvarien exclaimed, caught up in the moment. &quot;So harsh!&quot;<br>
<br>
Whiz's beeper started up again.<br>
<br>
&quot;Talv...&quot; Pedi warned, as the top of Whizbang's bald head started to go red.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shutting up!&quot; Talvarien said again, closing his mouth.<br>
<br>
&quot;Keep it zipped, half-breed!&quot; Whizbang snarled, and then looked over quickly to Grelin, the other half-elf. &quot;Sorry Grelin.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Sok.&quot; Grelin said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Anyway,&quot; Whizbang continued. &quot;The smell was horrid. So, I took down one of the rebreathers from the wall and strapped it on. At least being able to breathe again helped lighten my mood a bit. I'm still sweating, and I can't drown out those damned casino people, but at least I don't have to smell what Mrs. Brown's nag ate for dinner.<br>
<br>
The day continues, and the air is getting warm enough to the point where I'm going to complain. I get up and go to the Nexus side bank, and stand in line, fussing with the straps of the rebreather, which are giving me a problem.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, and if I wasn't so close to the ground I would have never seen it, this metal canister rolls across the floor from the Nexus entrance. Looked like part of an aqualung, that tinkered crap I used to make before I learned how to do rebreathers. Just rolls across the floor, hits the bank wall and stops, clink. I glance over towards the exit to see who dropped it, but i don't anyone there. I turn back to the bank, and way across the Bazaar, I see another of these canisters roll out from the Shadowhaven entrance, to hit the bank over there.<br>
<br>
Now I'm curious, as I see yet another little air tank roll in on the Shadowhaven side, and then almost trip over two more rolling in from the Nexus side. It's odd, but was also, menacing, in some strange way. I didn't like what I was seeing at all, and, forgetting all about my difficult rebreather and its snarled fasteners, I leaned over to pick up one of the cans.<br>
<br>
I never got the chance. Suddenly, one by one, the valves at the end pop, and a faint faint green mist starts to seep out. Rapidly. And as the mist hits air, it starts to...billow or something. Like it was reacting with the air and expanding as it hit oxygen. Pretty soon the whole front of the Bazaar is in a light green haze, in...seconds, it seemed. And it was just getting bigger.<br>
<br>
I'm alarmed now, and open the door to the bank to alert the Bazaar officials. And tripped over a body. Everyone in the bank was dead, or dying. One banker was clawing at his throat, eyes bulging out of his sockets. He saw me in my rebreather and tried to pull it off my face. He didn't even reach me before he was down dead. I climbed up on a stool to look out onto the Bazaar, and it was the same across as far as I could see. Everyone was dead. I mean, EVERYONE was dead. We lost at least five Walkers up there, the Bazaar was in full swing. And all dead. Except for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille was staring at him wideeyed. &quot;All those people dead. And you were spared....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;....because of horseshit, yes.&quot; Whizbang said.<br>
<br>
&quot;No wonder you had a heartattack, Whiz!&quot; Pedi exclaimed. &quot;Seeing all those people dead....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Bah!&quot; Whizbang replied. &quot;Takes more than mass-death to turn off my ticker. I've had your mother's cooking...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't equate my mother's cooking with a gas attack on the Bazaar!&quot; Pedi warned.<br>
<br>
&quot;Have you ever been around Ramluk after you toss him her leftovers?&quot; Whizbang rejoined.<br>
<br>
Beep beep beep.<br>
<br>
&quot;Go on Whiz.&quot; Pedi said sweetly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Err...&quot; Whizbang said, slowing down his rapid breathing. &quot;Ok, where was I? Ah, everyone was dead. And then, what should come into the Bazaar, into the green clouds as if it were air, from both the Shadowhaven entrance and the Nexus entrance?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What?&quot; Rocsalt said, intrigued by the entire story.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shissar!&quot; Whizbang exclaimed.<br>
<br>
&quot;The snakemen?&quot; Roc said in shock. &quot;From Shadowhaven?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot; Whizbang confirmed. &quot;They poured in two by two, more and more, till the place was swarming with them. And yes, I realized the implications of how they entered. If they came through Shadowhaven and the Nexus, then Shadowhaven most likely had suffered a similiar fate. They started picking through stalls, filling sacks with items. That's when I realized I was standing like a target on the stool, and jumped down and pulled one of the bankers bodies over me while I worked out what to do.<br>
<br>
Just in time too. Two shissar parked themselves outside the bank and started talking. They were talking their own language, but fortunately I learned shissar two weeks after we got to the moon, so other than some accent difficulty I had with it, I could understand them.<br>
<br>
'Is the Nexus disabled?' one said to the other.<br>
<br>
'Yes, Captain.' the other said, 'And he took care of the book there as well as the rest.'<br>
<br>
'Good.' the captain said. 'And the ports in?'<br>
<br>
'The cat outpost in the forest gave us trouble until the Grimlings overrode it, but it's secure now. Dawnshroud has been secure since two days ago, and Twilight was locked when Katta fell. We have the areas surrounded with that rock and set constantly in flames. Anyone porting in will find themselves trapped and burn to death.'<br>
<br>
'Excellent. Katta we will leave to the Coterie.' the captain said, and my skin is crawling now. Katta! The Geerlocks! Old friends, now gone. The death toll of people I knew was growing. If they had the force to take Katta, who knew if Seru was safe?<br>
<br>
'Seru was bloody, but over.' the lesser officer said, almost reading my mind.<br>
<br>
'Our people will maintain Shadowhaven and Seru.' the captain said. 'The Coterie will maintain Katta and the Grimlings can have Shar Vahl.'<br>
<br>
'They were to swarm Shar Vahl when we entered the Nexus. They outnumbered the cats ten to one, so I doubt there was any problem, sir.'<br>
<br>
'Good, good.' the Captain hissed. 'Now to the business of paying him for his help with keeping the outworlders from assisting.'<br>
<br>
'What are we to give him? So many things in here.'<br>
<br>
'He is to get every tinkered item, every piece of ore, every gem, every sheet of metal we can find. Also, meltable weaponry, anything not so infused with magic as to render it useless in a forge.'<br>
<br>
'Would simply be easier to impress the Grimlings to mine the ore he needs from acrylia...'<br>
<br>
'It was suggested.' the captain said. 'But that would put his project 'back a month'. So he insisted on all the metal from here. The Emperor agreed, so start on the Shadowhaven side, and sweep this area with your soldiers.'<br>
<br>
'Yes sir.' the lesser officer said, and then, louder. 'All you men, you know what to collect. Follow me to the Shadowhaven side, and we work towards Nexus.'<br>
<br>
His voice grew fainter as he drew away from the bank. I waited till I couldn't hear their hissing anymore, and climbed out from under the banker. I invised myself, and thought about gating out to warn people. I had no idea who this 'he' was that the two snakes had referred to, but apparently 'he' had masterminded the plan, locked out Norrath from the moon, selling out all the good people of Luclin for this roomful of metal. That pissed me off to no end.<br>
<br>
So, my decision was made. I quickly, invisibly, made my way back to my stall.<br>
<br>
I didn't waste any time, not knowing how long it would be before the snakes worked tehir way to my area. I stacked three cases of fire water and opened a fourth. Filling up a bowl with more fire water, I dropped a long coil of the twine I use for fuses for fireworks into it and let it soak. Then I took yet another bottle of fire water and poured it all over the unopened cases. Then, after doing a little math and calculating the best area of effect compared to other tinkers' stands, as well as the few people that liked to sell booze or fireworks, I shifted the boxes over 5 feet to the right. I then grabbed my soaked twine and fed one end into the whole mess, and snuck my way out of the Bazaar through the Nexus exit, laying the string down behind me. Finally I was out of string, but I was in the Nexus around the corner from the entrance.<br>
<br>
O'Keil's Embers was never put to better use than at that moment.<br>
<br>
The string caught fire instantly, and like the moons biggest firecracker, the fuse began to burn quickly. I turned to run to Netherbian Lair, to make sure it went off. They may have taken out every civilized area on the moon, but I was taking mess of them out in return.<br>
<br>
I turn to run, and smack face first into a human. But what armor! I felt as if I had run straight into a brick wall. Even with the rebreather over my face, my head throbbed. The human picked me up like a ragdoll and hung me in front of his face.<br>
<br>
'What are you doing, gnome?' he growled at me. The voice sent a chill right through me. But the visual was worse.<br>
<br>
It was River.<br>
<br>
Gods strike me dead if I am lying, but Riverdane Wyldechylde was holding me up as if I weighed nothing and looking at me with the most violent look I have ever seen on his face. And his face! His hair! All grey, as if he had painted himself the same shade of gray from head to foot. But his eyes, they showed no recognition of who I was, just hatred....and something else. Madness.<br>
<br>
So I'm swinging there, trapped, as the fuse burns its way back to my bomb in the Bazaar. I'm struggling, but River begins to shake me. And that's when I felt something like a hand clamp down on my heart, and my left arm starts getting this shooting pain.<br>
<br>
And then boom my supply of firewater goes up.<br>
<br>
Then boom boom boom as other flammables and explosives start to blow, pieces of the wall falling down as the smoke begins billowing from the Bazaar. River drops me and turns to gape at the smoking entrance, and I start trying to run, staggering as the pain becomes unbearable in my arm, knowing the big explosion I calculated hadn't happened yet.<br>
<br>
Then...<br>
<br>
BOOM. A tremendous ground shaking explosion, and I see the ceiling starting to fall onto the Bazaar, the Nexus. And meanwhile, my breath is growing short and I think I am going to pass out. So as my consciousness is going, I try to manage to gesture through my Greater Fay port, while the Bazaar is buried under rubble, and River begins cursing at the entrance like a crazy man. Just as I'm finishing the spell, and ready to die from the pain at this point, he turns to me. A rock falls from the ceiling and strikes him across his grey forehead, but he shrugs it off as if a fly, moving toward me with hate in his eyes. <br>
<br>
'YOU!' he says, reaching for me.<br>
<br>
But poof, I was gone.&quot;<br>
