<br>
&quot;He certainly didn't act like the River I knew, but the likeness was too precise for me to be mistaken.&quot; Whizbang said with complete faith.<br>
<br>
&quot;It was Grieg the Geomancer.&quot; Camille said.<br>
<br>
Whizbang blinked. &quot;Greig Veneficus?&quot; he asked, disbelief etched on his face. &quot;Grieg Veneficus died locked in his castle on the moon many many years before River was ever a twinkle in Innoruuk's pants...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No,&quot; Camille interrupted, shaking her head. &quot;That's why I came here.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Your turn, my girl.&quot; Whizbang said. &quot;Why exactly DID you come here, other than my wife mistakenly thinking I was calling for you. I'm glad you came, but I was referring to River with 'Wyldechylde'.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll tell you,&quot; Camille said, &quot;and maybe you can make some sense out of all of this, but you have to promise to stay calm.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He promises.&quot; Pedi said, fixing him with a look.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah, yeah, I promise, just ask Pedi.&quot; Whizbang said, settling back.<br>
<br>
And Cami filled Whiz in on every event that had transpired from her first nightmare.<br>
<br>
To his credit, Whizbang only sent the machine into convulsions twice during the entire tale, which Pedi excused, considering by the end of Cami's story, her own heart would have given her sick husband's a race.<br>
<br>
&quot;So that's why I'm here,&quot; Camille finished. &quot;CAN such a machine be built?&quot;<br>
<br>
Whizbang's brows were furrowed as he contemplated her question. &quot;Well, obviously Grieg thinks so. And considering that he helped effectively seal off the moon, trapped River into a power source, broke free of a goddess' prison, I'd have to say we must assume he can and will. Fortunately, my little stunt in the Bazaar may have bought us time. Mining the ore through the Grimlings will put his 'project back a month'. Digging out the Bazaar will take about as long, if what I saw falling onto it continued to fall. Let's assume he will have to go the mining route now, which gives us a month and whatever time he needs to build this...thing that will move the moon.&quot;<br>
<br>
Then he shook his head, thinking on everything Camille had said. &quot;Amazing. Haunting, or possession, from my understanding, is usually a very personal thing, but somehow Grieg has figured out a way to actually bind a soul to this Geomancer's Stone.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't understand.&quot; Camille said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, haunting comes in a few forms, but is usually from lifetimes of creating a bond with a place or object. When a person dies, according to most theologians, and backed by studies or talks with deities themselves, the spirit is free from the body. If the body is repairable, it has roughly three hours to be repaired and 'resurrected' through the aide of a cleric. That's all resurrection is...the cleric, or very skilled paladins, acting as a guide to bring the confused and lost soul back to its body, which your healing powers has restored. Druids, shaman, other healers can restore the body, but it takes a spiritual faith to guide the soul back. Clerics and paladins are taught those techniques, tho they think of them as more of a gift from their god, than the science it is. The mere force of their belief is what makes it possible. The other healers are focused on other things, the animal world, the world of nature, etc. and don't have that pure faith that they can raise the dead, so, lacking the conviction, also lack the strength to do it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pedi frowned at how neatly he had turned her gift into some sort of act of zeal, but they had had that argument many times in the past, and she wasn't going to stop him now, while his beeper wasn't beeping.<br>
<br>
&quot;So, then we have those souls who move on, no longer able to rejoin their body. Some get old unoccupied bodies, like my guildee Bonlainy did, but these instances are extremely rare and more freak occurances than what would be considered the norm. Some other spirits would linger in their old homes and residences, bonding to a location and 'haunting' it. Others yet would bond to a nearby personal object. Lockets have been haunted by former possessers, even one lost spirit went so far as to haunt his old suit of armor and marched up and down the halls of Kaladim, driving the dwarves there to distraction until they were able to 'exorcise' the spirit out.<br>
<br>
Others, most spirits, would seek the god they worshiped, and then would be in that god's possession. In some cases, there would be a form of paradise, or hell, awaiting them, depending on that particular god's whims. In some cases, like Vven's, they continue on in spirit form, aiding their god. Others, like River, are sent to dream (a paradise? a hell? only River knew) until woken to protect their god, or godess, in this case. In River's case, the need to be able to protect his goddess put him into a physical form, in this 'soul casing', a living rock that could be powered by a soul. Similiar to the possessed suit of armor, except it is much much stronger, needing a raid force, if the battle you told me about was accurate, to destroy.&quot;<br>
<br>
Camille nodded, recalling how long it took Promethian Order to take down the four gargoyles in Terris' lair.<br>
<br>
&quot;So now Grieg is in possession of this living statue, and River is going to be consumed, soul gone, in.....a month? Two, at most, I'm thinking, in order to power this engine Grieg is going to use to move the moon. But Grieg's plan is flawed, very flawed, and will mean his destruction as well. He is foolish to not see that, but I have the feeling he knows, and his madness prevents him from caring. But his revenge is going to affect many many more than just the children, tho they will undoubtably suffer the most.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Whiz,&quot; Camille asked, overwhelmed by the enormity of all of this, &quot;What can we do? CAN we do anything?&quot;<br>
<br>
The question hung in the air pregnantly. Every eye in the room watched the gnome, whose eyes were at the moment closed in thought.<br>
<br>
Then they blinked open, tired, but clear.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot; he said. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 405<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/14/03 1:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> &quot;We must keep this a secret.&quot; Whizbang said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Secret?&quot; Talvarien exclaimed. &quot;Why not get CC, EA, Triality and the other guilds together and go in powpowpowpow and take back the moon? If PO alone could take on four of those gargoyles and Terris, it should be no prob...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Because,&quot; Whiz said matter-of-factly. &quot;No matter how strong the ubers think they are, almost all of their power derives from magic. How many of them do you see walking around in fine steel plate? And with Grieg having discovered, for lack of a better word, these null stones that cancel magic, many of them would be walking into a slaughter. The Nexus is shut down. The portals are awash in fire, and anyone porting in will not only face that, but being stripped of all buffs and their magical items becoming mere useless trinkets. And even if they send the casters and melee bound on the moon, those few who still are, where would they end up? Most of them in the Bazaar, buried in rock. Or if not the Bazaar or the Nexus, spread out thinly over the face of the moon. No, Luclin is closed to us. So, instead, word will leak here, and a panic will begin.<br>
<br>
There are enough intelligent minds to know, just among the casters alone, what will happen if the moon shifts. The tides are controlled by the gravitational pull of Luclin. When Luclin grows closer to Norrath, the seas will rise up, swallowing the lower lands. People will flee to higher ground, but by then, earthquakes will shake the grounds, volcanos will rise and spew molten rock into the air, the world will be covered by ash. The ash will cloud the world and the suns rays would never touch it. Or, if the moon ends up in the wrong position, it may block the sun entirely, sending us into perpetual night and an ice age that will make Ice Clad look like a tropical paradise. Meanwhile, and this leads me to believe Grieg's allies are unaware of his plans, the same thing will be happening on Luclin, as the moon feels a greater tug from Norrath's pull. They will slowly draw toward one another, until they collide, and that will be the end of both worlds.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But they'll have time!&quot; Talvarien countered, &quot;Flee to the planes! Run away, port!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, the planes.&quot; Whizbang said gravely. &quot;Yes, that will be their last recourse. And with the books gone,they will have to mass port, and quickly. And what will happen then? Well, all the children and people of insufficient experience in their craft will be locked into the Plane of Knowledge, unable to enter the higher planes. With no way to formally train in the Plane of Knowledge, they will never advance high enough to enter Tranquility and beyond. Eventually that small Plane of Knowledge would fill, with no food imported, and no room for livestock and farmland. The planes that do not have hostile environments may be used for farmland, but all this would do would be to limit the living space. Sex of any kind would be made illegal, for fear of bringing more children into the world, more mouths to feed. Races would lose their heritage, having no homeland anymore, and the new nations would become the individual guilds, us and them. And all those souls that die on Norrath! The planes occupied by the gods would be filled to capacity! Eventually, as things become more desperate, guild would fall upon guild, as civilization breaks down and it becomes a contest of the strongest vs. the weak. Guild clerics would be the first targets, and the paladins, and even the necros, with their artificial way of resurrecting the dead. And then with lack of resurrection, life as we know it would eventually dwindle to the few strong, and then...die.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Mithaniel help us...&quot; Camille prayed out loud, picturing the destruction Whiz laid out and seeing plainly how possible it was.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, that's exactly what we'll need.&quot; Whizbang said, hearing her whispered prayer. &quot;Let me tell you my plan.&quot;  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 407<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/16/03 1:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> I will stall the guilds here. Whizbang  said, Tell them the Shissar, Coterie and Grimlings have formed an alliance and have driven out the Norrathians.  I will explain the situation with the portals and hope they arent too pigheaded to listen.  Ill let them know we have people on the moon working on remedying the situation.<br>
<br>
People, what people?  Talvarien asked.<br>
<br>
Whizbang raised his free arm and pointed at Camille.  You, Camille.  And the rest of you.<br>
<br>
Whiz Camille began.<br>
<br>
Hear me out. The gnome said, cutting off her protest.  We need to get Grieg taken out.  He is key to all of this.  You know what to look for.  You know the Geomancers Stone.  You would recognize Grieg.  Knowing your husbands eternal soul is at stake, you will have the will to go on where others may falter.  You have a tracker, a healer, and a puller.  You have a porter at your disposal.  And keeping it small, you have stealth, which is the most important thing.  Grieg must be separated from Rivers soul casing.  And the Geomancers Stone must be taken from Griegs possession.  Would you trust anyone else with Rivers soul, Camille?<br>
<br>
No. Camille said.<br>
<br>
As I expected.  Whizbang nodded.<br>
<br>
But Whiz, Camille said, It took Promethian Order with a full raid almost as much time as it took to down Terris to destroy those other statues.  How are we going to even touch Grieg?<br>
<br>
Thats where your little prayer is going to help us.<br>
<br>
Mithaniel Marr? Camille asked.<br>
<br>
Aye. Whizbang replied.  Paladins, as a class, have an almost obscene number of quested swords available to them, and only them.  The Soulfire, the Fiery Defender and Avenger, are just a fraction of the paladin-only weapons Marr with his obsession with honor through combat has created.  There is a little sought after weapon, covered by some obscure lore, by the name of  Earthcarver.  Have you ever heard of it?<br>
<br>
Earthcarver? Camille blinked.  No, never.<br>
<br>
I didnt think you would have.  Why it was ever conceived in the first place always seemed a mystery to me.  It is a weapon singular in purpose, and so fragile in its construction it can only be used once.  But its power, simple as it may be, is exactly what you need.<br>
<br>
What does it do? Camille asked.<br>
<br>
It can cut through anything.  Whizbang said.  A finishing blade, one that will not be hampered by shield, armor.or stone.  One swing and it destroys itself, but it cuts through anything like a hot knife through butter.<br>
<br>
Earthcarver. Camille repeated.  Where can I find the blade?<br>
<br>
You do not find it. Whizbang said apologetically.  You make it.<br>
<br>
Make it?<br>
<br>
Go to Mithaniel.  He will provide you with the instructions to construct the blade. Whizbang said.  The lore does not explain its creation, just that it is a quest given by the god Marr himself.<br>
<br>
Whiz, you havent covered another issue. Rocsalt said through the gauze covering his face.  How do we, once we create this blade, get to the moon?  Grelin porting in to Dawnshroud will just result in us burning quicker than if Solesek Ro himself lit us up.<br>
<br>
Yeah! Talvarien exclaimed.  Ranja Extra-Crispy is NOT on the menu!<br>
<br>
Brimstone, Whizbang said.  When we couldnt port during End Game, River used the horse to travel.  Terris took back the horse, but could you persuade her to let you borrow it for this?<br>
<br>
Whiz. Camille said, shaking her head doubtfully.  When Terris was directly commanding it, it bore me.  But the horse has tried to kill me for a year.  Even when Terris commanded it to bring me to her, it tried to shake me.  It bonded with River, but otherwise, its a willful creature, and I think it hates me, jealousy maybe over Rivers attention on me.  It was mutual.  I doubt if Terris gave it to me that I would be able to control it.<br>
<br>
Hmmph. Whizbang said, brow furled.  Then ask Mithaniel your best course on how to access the moon.  If the gods were going to get involved in this they would have, is my guess, so we have to assume we are on our own here.  In fact, I would imagine some, fearing when we finally break into the Plane of Time, would see the destruction of both worlds as a blessing.  Mithaniel is the God of Honor.  He may not help you directly, but I expect he will not hinder you either.  If he offers no solution, maybe I will have one tomorrow.  Now, Im tired.<br>
<br>
Its three in the morning. Pedi observed.   You need your sleep, and so do I, old man.<br>
<br>
And I. Rocsalt said.  Talvarien nodded as well.<br>
<br>
I slept all day. Camille said, You guys go back to the guildhouse and Ill head to the Halls of Honor.  Its best I go alone anyway.<br>
<br>
No argument there.  Rocsalt replied, nodding.  Ive destroyed enough white suits to put me on the most wanted list there.<br>
<br>
Ill take you. Grelin said to Camille.<br>
<br>
Thank you Grelin. she replied.  Whiz, can I come by in the morning when youve awaken?<br>
<br>
Aye, Whizbang said, eyes heavy.  In the morning.<br>
<br>
And you, Pedi said, pointing to Rocsalt.  Come with her.  I want to talk to someone about your cough.<br>
<br>
Will do. Rocsalt said, self-consciously touching his throat.<br>
<br>
Hey. Talvarien said suddenly, Do we take Ramluk with us?<br>
<br>
I said stealth, not go in with a ten piece band.  Whizbang said.  No, Ramluk would be more of a problem than a help.  Its bad enough we have the ranger that shoots off his mouth more than his bow.<br>
<br>
Hey! Talvarien cried, insulted.  I dont shoot off my mouth<br>
<br>
Prove it. Whizbang said automatically.<br>
<br>
Talvarien opened his mouth to speak, and Whizbang just raised an eyebrow.  Talv closed his mouth without another word.<br>
<br>
Ok, Grelin. Camille said.  Lets get these two home, and thento the Planes.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 408<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/16/03 1:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Everything was so.white.<br>
<br>
White marble floors, white marble columns, white flying buttresses and arches, white stretching west, for as far as her eyes could see.  The only other colors black and green; the green of the hedges flanking and the walkways and the black of the unoccupied suits of armor standing sentry at the entrance.<br>
<br>
You look tired. Camille said to Grelin, who stood blinking in the bright light of the Halls of Honor.<br>
<br>
Yeah. Grelin said.  Long day.<br>
<br>
Go back to the guildhouse and get some rest.  Ill find a way back. Camille released him.<br>
<br>
Grelin simply nodded, murmured something arcane, and disappeared.  Camille turned back to those inanimate suits of armor and prepared to walk through them.  She would be safe here, she hoped.  But she could not help but shiver.  Somewhere in this white architecture, not too long ago, one of her friends and his dog had stained the floors red with their blood.<br>
<br>
Fall out! she heard someone say deep within.  And then the sound of men in armor marching, in perfect time, left right across the marble floors.<br>
<br>
The Halls of Honor.  One of the two planes desired to be the resting place of any paladin.  For the less aggressive paladins, this was their final destination.  For those of a more warlike nature, there existed the ongoing battles in the Plane of Valor.  Camille had long ago dreamed of spending her final time here.  Now it just seemed cold.  She would have chosen to stand as a statue opposite her husband in the gloomy recesses of Terris Thule without a moments hesitation.  But now, even that was taken from her.<br>
<br>
She began to make her way through the two jet black suits of ornate armor.  Suddenly the left one advanced toward her, drawing its sword.  Reaver whisked out of its scabbard.   So it was to be a fight after all.<br>
<br>
Leave her. came an empty voice resonating from the other suit.  He says to let her pass.<br>
<br>
The advancing suit stopped, turned perfectly in time and marched back to its previous post without a word.  Camille nodded to the right suit, sheathing her weapon, feeling a little foolish acknowledging an empty suit of armor, but knowing at one time it had been a living paladin, one of her class, and had had the same drive to bring light to a dark world as she.  And into the plane she marched.<br>
<br>
It is now time for the changing of the guard! another voice said from somewhere within the statuary and hedges.  And westward she walked, passing men in beautifully wrought armor going through vigorous training, and one pen full of creatures that resembled some hybrid cross between a lion and dog.  They were babies yet, mewling for milk or playfully tumbling, swatting at each other with paws that had yet to develop claws.  But even as infants they were the size of a small bear.   She could only imagine the size of their parents.<br>
<br>
After some time she came to the base of a mountain, with unscalable walls.  A large portal was erected, the face of it alive with lightning, electricity running along its columns, up and down.  Two human knights stood guard to either side,  standing at seven feet, almost two heads taller than she.  High up on the mountain, she saw a similar portal, tiny in the distance.  She realized she was to walk through the lightning to reach her destination.<br>
<br>
Steeling herself for a shock, a burn, something, she strode forward.  Both guards saluted her with perfect precision, but she kept her eyes ahead, and stepped into the light.<br>
